          "body": "The census of 38,000 (23:3) is staggering — roughly one in twenty Israelites, by some estimates, dedicated to the service of God's house. The four-fold functional division that follows (23:4-5) is theologically revealing: 24,000 overseers of temple work, 6,000 officers and judges, 4,000 gatekeepers, and 4,000 musicians/praisers. That the largest single group is assigned to temple oversight signals the Chronicler's conviction that the house of God demands the most sustained human labor. That 4,000 full-time praisers are created — playing instruments David himself made (23:5) — signals something else: praise is not a worship supplement but a primary Levitical vocation, equal in dignity to gatekeeping and judicial service. David consecrates his artistic creativity (the instruments he made) to the service of God's glory. The Chronicler will develop the musicians in detail in chapters 25 and elsewhere; here they appear as one of the four pillars of the new worship order."
